@reimsn_ufort called upon. 
It is essential that the RSAF continues to remain vigilant, and maintains our operational readiness to defend our skies and country. As training and daily operations remain an integral and important part to the RSAF in order to defend our country, we seek your understanding and look forward to your continued support for Total Defence.

@reimsn_ufort We are writing in response to your feedback dated 28 Apr 2020, regarding the noise generated from the flying activities conducted by the Republic of Singapore Air Force (RSAF). The RSAF is mindful of the need to balance the interests of our residents with the critical need to maintain our operational readiness. However, due to constraints such as Singapore’s limited airspace, the locations of our air bases and the need to minimise disruption to civilian air traffic, RSAF aircraft may fly over certain residential areas during the take-off or landing phases of a flight. 
Our flying training is conducted over waters for the majority of a flight, rather than landmasses. However, there are small portions of a flight that will require our aircraft to fly over landmasses such as during the take-off phase (aircraft will be on climb to a high altitude for transit to the training areas), the landing phase of a flight (where aircraft will need to descend to a low altitude to prepare for landing) or during the conduct of circuit training (where pilots practise take-off and landing to ensure that they are able to handle the aircraft safely). Outside of this, our aircraft do not fly over residential areas for prolonged periods. 
We are cognisant of the current circuit breaker measures and that many of our residents are working from home. However, critical operations to safeguard Singapore – such as island defence, protection of key installations, maritime security and air defence operations – continue to be performed around the clock. As such, there may be instances where there are flying activities conducted periodically as our units and personnel need to remain competent in their skill sets. Please be assured that the conduct of flying activities from Paya Lebar Air Base is not continuous over prolonged periods. 
We would also like to explain that our daily flying intensity has been reduced, and spread out across the weekdays and on selected weekends as our critical operational units are cohorted into various teams. The current level of flying training activities is the minimum required to ensure our pilots remain proficient to carry out their tasks when
